	sylb:schedule "第1回 Introduction, Health Survey and Basic Life Support（担当：Yoko Hamada）
Course progression, final report details and grading policy will 
be explained. A health survey will be conducted in order to 
evaluate his/her own health condition. 
Are you familiar with the AED(Automated External Defibrillator) 
device? AED devices are widely installed in public locations in 
Japan. The AED device is designed for popular use in the case 
ventricular fibrillation or cardiac arrest intervention is 
necessary. This lecture will brief the basic guidelines for 
emergency rescue, including the use of AED devices, so that all 
students will be able to respond to situations requiring critical 
care

第2回 Alcohol and Smoking　（担当：Hirokazu　Yokoyama）
Occasions involving the consumption of alcohol increase greatly 
after university enrollment. Needless to say, minors are 
prohibited from consuming alcohol; however the reasons why and 
the risks surrounding minors and alcohol will be considered, as 
well as acute alcohol poisoning following binge drinking or 
“ikki-nomi”. An alcohol patch test will be conducted to confirm 
levels of ethanol metabolism in order to derive optimal drinking 
habits. The risks of smoking and nicotine dependence, alongside 
drug dependence, will be explained 


Intercultural Adjustment I-IV will be 4 interactive sessions on 
intercultural adjustment from both intercultural communication 
and psychology perspective using a variety of student –centered 
activities including art and bodywork. 

第3回 Intercultural Adjustment I: Introduction（担当：Kaoru Yamamoto）
Intercultural Adjustment I will be an introductory session.　 
Students will reflect on their life in Japan and to identify 
areas where they want to work on to enjoy life in Japan. We will 
also explore the question of multicultural identity. The 
Landscape Montage Technique and metaphoric communication method 
will be used to assist self-reflection and the group discussions.

第4回 Intercultural Adjustment II（担当：Kaoru Yamamoto）
This will be an interactive session for learning about the 
process of intercultural adjustment. The purposes of this session 
are to understand one’s own psycho-physical reactions to the 
unknown, and to identify which behavioral options allow one to 
thrive in an intercultural setting. One of the keys to 
successful adjustment is “the ability to transform negative 
emotion to positive energy” (Jackie Wasilewski). We will focus 
on managing stress which one encounters in the course of adapting 
to a new environment, and explore ways to communicate with 
ourselves, with others, and with our environment to make a 
successful transformation.

第5回 Intercultural Adjustment III（担当：Kaoru yamamoto）
Successful intercultural adjustment to make the best of your life 
in Japan. This session is designed to provide the students with 
opportunities to apply and integrate what they have learned so 
far about intercultural adjustment in order to optimize it and to 
thrive as a student in Japan. Using a case study of an 
intercultural counseling in Japan, we will discuss potential 
mental health problems in intercultural maladjustment, explore 
personal, cultural, situational, and other factors that trigger 
intercultural maladjustment, and to identify what we can do to 
prevent them. We will also examine intercultural maladjustment as 
a driving force for personal growth, too.

第6回 Intercultural Adjustment IV（担当：Kaoru Yamamoto）
Wrap up and Q&A

第7回 Lifestyle-related disease and prevention of Infectious disease.（担当：Yoko Hamada）
International students undoubtedly experience substantial changes 
in diet, sleep and other areas of their lifestyle. This lecture 
aims to deepen the understanding of how diet and exercise affect 
and related to lifestyle and lifestyle-related disease and will 
further focus on the practical application of theory. 
In addition, various nations have their own standards of 
infectious disease prevention measures, to which the student is 
subject to. This lecture will outline prevention measures adopted 
in Japan and the possible infectious diseases to which you may be 
susceptible

その他
Final report:Wellness plan

